#X text 43 25 A Complex number has a real and an imaginary part \, hence it's a bi dimensional number that can be represented in a cartesian plane as below \, where the real part is the horizontal axis and the imaginary the vertical axis. We can relate this to the last example \, where the Cosine amplitude is the real part and the Sine amplitude is the imaginary part., f 56;
#X text 498 154 real part;
#X text 661 152 imaginary part;
#X text 497 190 Cartesian to Polar, f 9;
#X text 836 249 (in radians);
#X text 533 284 Polar to Cartesian, f 9;
#X text 667 339 Imaginary;
#X text 709 378 Cartesian to Polar;
#X text 706 465 Polar to Cartesian;
#X text 526 635 Audio versions:;
#X text 768 421 Phase;
#X text 834 227 Initial Phase;
#X obj 645 534 mag;
#X floatatom 645 587 8 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X text 574 587 Amplitude;
#X obj 792 634 mag~;
#X obj 786 17 declare -path else;
#X obj 58 149 pic 0 euler.gif empty empty 0 0;
#X text 31 618 The cartesian representation of a complex number is by its (a \, b) coordinates \, but you can also represent it in the Polar form \, composed of the "magnitude" (amplitude) and "argument" (Initial Phase).;
#X text 31 518 A complex number is defined as a + b*i \, where "a" is the real part \, and b is a real number mupltiplied by the imaginary unit "i" (which is the square root of -1). We use complex math for FFT \, but when dealing with it in Pd we just actually deal with the real numbers "a" and "b" \, though it is implied that b is multiplied by "i"., f 58;
#X obj 771 277 rad2deg;
#X floatatom 771 309 8 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X text 833 309 (in degrees);
#X text 561 676 see also:;
#X obj 642 676 deg2rad;
#X obj 712 676 rad2deg;
#X text 490 52 We actually already did the conversion from cartesian to polar in the last example. Let's see now how to converto to and back with [expr] and objects from the ELSE library. Note that the phase is now in radians \, but you can convert it from and to degrees with the [rad2deg] and [deg2rad] objects from ELSE., f 63;
